column8: P1. A universal, public, and unified healthcare system, where people pay according to their income, would ensure healthcare access for everyone.
column9: P2. Encouraging more personal responsibility by abolishing mandatory health insurance and increasing out-of-pocket payments.
column10: P3. No changes are needed to the current healthcare system, as it functions well as it is.
column11: P4. More government control over pricing and greater financial support (e.g., individual premium subsidies) would help those in need.
column12: P5. Fixing financial inefficiencies in the healthcare system could save a lot of money without major changes to the system.
column13: P6. Less government regulation and more private competition would make healthcare more efficient and cost-effective.
